Hi - I've built this up and have it running on my M150! :)
I've been running a Diii cooler but found I was always crouching down to try and see if the first layer had gone down correctly, trying to spot little bits of the print as the head moved and made small sections viewable ... so the cobra works very well for me.
The design has the arm hanging around the right hand side of the print head, this means the head won't move all the way to the right edge of the build plate without hitting the frame. I can see that the arm could be modified to sling the front-to-back length underneath the extruder stepper which would remove this issue ... but as I don't generally print anything big enough to cause the problem I'm going to keep running it as it is.
Thanks for the effort to put this together.

title: Super simple upgraded Kossel Mini effector

description.text:
I've had a Kossel Mini for a while and I wanted to give it a elegant and functional effector which could improve print quality and offer a certain benefits like a part cooling.

This is a upgrade for a standard magnetic Kossel Mini effector and compatible with E3D v6 and it's (very similar) clones.

The thing is entirely printable WITHOUT support!

Upgraded effector to version 1.1. Following were improved/changed:

  • Added support for IR differential height sensor (https://miscsolutions.wordpress.com/mini-height-sensor-board/) - soon I will add instructions how to mount it.
  • Slightly adjusted the fan mounting holes.
  • Redesigned the fan duct and placed the mounting holes to better positions. There are two versions of fan ducts - with or without IR probe mounts.

E1: In the distant future I'm going to improve this design by a more convenient fan connections, z-probe (probably modified IR probe) and lights.

E2: As soon as I get hold on IR differential height sensor there will be an upgraded fan ducts for mounting this. - DONE!

E3: I noticed the effector reduces printing area to 170mm circle, beyond that magnetic rods will crash into fan's side and mess up everything. I'll plan to fix this issue in the following week. - Unfortunately there is no room for fans to move closer to the heat sink which means that 170mm circle is your absolute maximum print area. On the other side - commonly used purple heatbed has same dimensions, so it should't be much of a issue.

E4: Added modified fan duct for E3D Volcano. Since I don't have Volcano myself, someone should confirm if its usable or not. I used the dimensions from E3D data sheet so it can't be too much off. Both versions, with or without dc42's IR sensor are available.

E5: Upgraded effector body to version 1.2. Following were improved/changed:

  • Added M3 nut traps to the effector body for attaching E_mount and E_duct. Not they can be fastened without the fear of overtightening the screw and therefore ruining the hole.
  • Three holes on the top (for attaching E_mount) must be slightly (0,2 mm) drilled with 3mm drill bit. It is to avoid the unnecessary mess in the nut trap.
  • Some chamfers were added to smooth up the air flow.
  • Holes for the fan wires were repositioned and enlarged.
  • Added *.sldprt file for the new version as well. It should open with Fusion 360 or Solidworks 2017+.
  • Now E_mount and E_duct are using 6 mm M3 screws. You need 6 in total + 6 M3 nuts.
  • All previous parts should be compatible.

Coming soon:

  • I'll tidy up the BOM
  • Some additional nut traps for the fans (goal is to get at least 2 for a fan).
  • Discovering an options for an easily attachable and removable cable harness.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

No

Resolution:

Infill:

100%

Notes:

It is designed to be printed without support material. At least my Ultimaker 2 handled it very nicely, so if you are skeptical, you might add some support.
I would recommend to use PLA for printing this, since it's stiffer than ABS and does not shrink while cooling. Although, fan mounts could be printed with ABS, but it's not necessary.

There's a list of the parts I used with Aliexpress links.

  • 12 mm ring magnets - https://goo.gl/1oisRh
  • Set of M3 screws - https://goo.gl/85M558
  • Screwdriver for M3 screws (hex 9)
  • Few M3 nuts: https://goo.gl/JsRqTD
  • Cable ties: https://goo.gl/QelxPP
  • Fans: https://goo.gl/IYplOu - I strongly recommend these ones!
  • Superglue
  • Heat shrink or isolating tape
  • Soldering stuff: soldering iron and solder
  • Some wire
  • Aluminum tape (not necessary)
  • Bowden clip (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1620721/#files)

If you are using a Ramps 1.4 board with heated bed then you'll have to make/buy a fan extender to control part and hotend cooling separately.
Option 1 - buy: https://goo.gl/ZPmqKN
Option 2 - make: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:22202 or https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:723781

When buying parts for the fan extender make sure that you but at least 2x the parts you'll need. I got this thing right with a third try, so give some room for an error.

Preparations

Firstly make sure that all your printed parts fit together nicely and don't have any printing defects that may affect printers printing quality afterwards. I had some aluminum tape laying around, so I covered the bottom of the effector with the tape to reflect off some excess heat but in retrospect I would say it does not matter if you do so or not.

Connecting the fans

You will have to cut off the plastic terminals from the fan wire in order to pass the wire through the small hole between the hotend camber and part cooling fans chamber.

Then cut to length two parts of longer wire in order to connect fans with your printer electronics
board. Those wires should be as long as heating cartridges wires. It's helpful to mark those wires so you could remember afterwards which is which. Put those wires into the small hole on the side of the effector.

Trim the fan wires to extend few centimeters off the wall they're coming from and solder the two part cooling fans to the first wire pair and hotend cooling fan to the other wire pair. Cover the contacts with isolating tape or heat shrink.

After that you can fix both part cooling fans, but leave the hotend cooling fan loose.

Put together your E3D v6 hotend and make a little fold to the heater cartridges cable. It is necessary to fit a cable through its slot afterwards.

Mounting the hotend

Before you put hotend into the effector guide the cable through it's slot. If you don't do it now, then it's impossible to do afterwards without taking assembly apart. When hotend is in place screw in the first holder (with two screw holes) and after that the second, but connect it with the first holder before and watch that the heater blocks orientation is correct.

I would recommend to add a bowden clip (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1620721/#files) to the hotend to ensure the tube stays in place and does not come loose. I experienced the issue and its not very convenient thing to fix.

Glue the magnets

At the beginning i hoped that magnets will stay in with friction, so they could be reused for future projects, but they came loose after some printing. Therefore I would recommend to use super glue to fix your magnets.

Mount the air ducts

I put some aluminum tape to the air ducts in order to give them a bit better thermal resistance, but the glue came loose and the tape fell off. Since then I haven't put the tape back and they seem to be unaffected by the heat.

Mount them to the bottom of the effector.

IR differential height probe

Version 1.1 supports IR differential height probe (https://miscsolutions.wordpress.com/mini-height-sensor-board/) which will be mounted between the fan ducts. If you don't care about the probe then print out the ducts without probe mount.

Firstly attach probe to the fan ducts (it may require some plastic bending to get this thing done).

I found it easier to connect the wire before attaching fan ducts to the effector. Notice that there is a small slot for 28G 3-braid wire.

Cable management

There's a special slot for the 2,5mm zip tie to hold your cables.

I used Ramps 1.4 board with Repetier software.

Since Ramps does not support by default multiple controllable fans, you made a fan extender. Connect part cooling fans to the D9.
Hotend cooling fan's extender must be connected to the 12V and to the servo pin 11.

For the Repetier software you must change following things in Configuration.h

define EXTRUDER_FAN_COOL_TEMP 50 //temperautre when hotend fan starts working
define PDM_FOR_COOLER 1
define EXT0_EXTRUDER_COOLER_PIN 11 //pin where we are getting signal

And that's it. Now hotend fan should start working automatically when hotends temperature exceeds 50C and shuts down when below it.

For the IR probe you must change the following things in EEPROM. I recommend to use Repetier host for that kind of interactions.

Autolevel active - [1]
Z-probe height - [2] //you must calibrate your sensor to get exact value
Z-probe bed dist. - [4] //also benefits from calibration
Z-probe speed - [10]
Z-probe x-y-speed - [60]
Z-probe offset x - [0]
Z-probe offset y - [-15] //I got better results when this value was 0
Z-probe X1 - [-50]
Z-probe Y1 - [-50]
Z-probe X2 - [50]
Z-probe Y2 - [-50]
Z-probe X3 - [-50]
Z-probe Y3 - [50]

And in configuration.h

define FEATURE_Z_PROBE 1
define Z_PROBE_PIN ORIG_Z_MIN_PIN //that means you have to connect probe to z-min endstop on RAMPS board
define Z_PROBE_PULLUP 1
define Z_PROBE_ON_HIGH 1
define Z_PROBE_SWITCHING_DISTANCE 1
define Z_PROBE_REPETITIONS 2
define BED_LEVELING_METHOD 1
define BED_CORRECTION_METHOD 0
define BED_LEVELING_GRID_SIZE 5
define BED_LEVELING_REPETITIONS 3
define FEATURE_AXISCOMP 1

description.text:
This is a pocket toothpick holder. It holds 25-30 toothpicks. It screws tightly closed and opens up just enough to load and unload toothpicks, without spilling them all over the floor. When assembled, the canister is all one piece.

For assembly, the inner part is inserted through the bottom of the outer part until the rod extends through the canister, then the lid is screwed onto the rod until the threads are fully inside the lid. I used a pair of pliers to grip the center rod while attaching the lid to the rod. Then the canister is ready for operation.
UPDATE: v2 of the outer has been posted. It will help keep the stringing from happening on the inside if you print with the threaded end up.

UPDATE: You might need to rotate the STL file in your slicer program in order to print properly. They need to be printed upright. (not on their sides as shown in the above STL pics.) The lid should be printed flat, with the hole facing upwards.

description.text:
A module case for the DIY 4-in-1 multi-protocol module which allows use of the Turnigy 9XR Pro's internal antenna.

To use this case you may need to modify your multi-protocol module - I had to remove the 5-pin header connector from its original position on top of the board and re-solder it underneath. This was done to ensure a good connection with the module bay pins.

As I use my module in serial mode I also removed the bind button so that I could have a completely flush cover plate.

You will need an MCX to IPX/U.FL antenna cable, like this:
http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/262040276984

In truth 15cm is slightly too long, but the extra coax can be easily looped under the board. 7.5-10cm would probably be better.

I'm still tweaking and fine-tuning, but the parts are essentially functional at this point.

description.text:
Nameplate for a Lulzbot 3d printer! I provided the files for a single extruder or a triple extruder.

To get the single extruder multicolor print to work, I did this:

1) Load White filament and start the print and pause after the middle white circle has finished its final top layer.

2) Load Green filament and continue the print. Pause after the green base has finished its final top layer.

3) Load Black filament and continue the print until finished!
TinkerCAD user "colorado rc" already had the logo in TinkerCAD, so I just made a copy and modified it to be able to be printed in multiple colors.

description.text:
The purpose of this thing is to orderly and safely route the Hot End wiring harness from the back of the printer to the Hot End. A secondary function is to route the filament PTEF tube from the Extruder to the Hot End with minimal bends while maintaining clearance with the top cover of the printer.

The Hot End Cable Chain bracket is directly attached to the E3D V6 Bolt On Adapter (referenced below) via M3 bolts or Cable Ties. Alternately a revised Bold On Adapter is available which includes the Cable Chain Mount as part of the Base:

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1708182

The individual cable lines and retaining clips included here for convenience are from:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:193948

Install Cable Chain
  • POWER OFF PRINTER
  • Install 3ea M3 Lock Nuts in the aft Printer Mount using M3x10 screw to align the nut and draw it into the nut wells provided.
  • Install the Hot End Bracket using 3ea M3x10 Screws and nuts. Use washers under the screw head and also under the nuts.
  • Assemble 15 links into a chain and snap the assembly into the Printer and Hot End mounts.
  • Remove wiring harness from the Hot End and insert it into the Cable Chain.
  • Install 17 Retaining Clips
  • Plug wiring harness into Hot End Connector.
  • Secure wiring harness at the Hot End using a cable ties and the holes provided in the mount bracket.
  • Route the Filament PTFE tube under the Cable Chain as indicated in the attached photos.

Printer Attachment

All attachment hardware is M3x10 with locking nuts.

The aft portion of the Printer Attach Bracket contains M3 hex nut wells. This eases the attachment of the bracket since it is difficult to hold the nut while turning the screws.

The Hot End Cable Chain Bracket fastens to the cable tie eyelets no the E3D V6 adapter (referenced above) and can be modified to attach to other Hot Ends.

description.text:
Calibrating X and Y axis on the Original Prusa i3 MK2

UPDATE 5 April 2017 Changed reference from M501 to M503. Note that Prusa Research i3 MK2 firmware 3.0.10 allows you to save the PID settings directly. I have not yet tested that firmware, so will leave the instructions as they exist. This method still works for newer and older firmware.

UPDATE 25 January 2017 Calibration Square now has labels and an additional cross beam. Thanks to Jonas Hansen for helping me to create the initial version, and thanks to Kyle Wiehe for the updated version.

There are four axis' that can be calibrated on MK2, X (left to right), Y (front to back), Z (height) and E (extruder). I found my printer was printing pieces that were noticeably undersized, especially on the Y axis. Using the process recommended in the Instructables article linked below, I was able to quickly improve calibration in the X and Y axis.

Follow the steps below to calibration your X and Y axis:
1.Connect to your printer via a USB connection (direct to computer or Octoprint, etc.)

  1. Issue the M503 command
  2. Scroll back through the output of the M503 command and look for the M92 output. Mine was M92:X100.00 Y100.00 Z400.00 E161.30. Copy down these numbers. The M92 command sets the numbers of steps the stepper motors will move based on movement instructions in your GCODE
  3. Download, slice, and print the calibration square included with this Thing
  4. Before removing the square from the bed, note that the X-axis is left to right movement and Y axis is front to rear movement.
  5. Using calipers, measure the distance across the X-axis in at least three places. I suggest measuring 10mm from each end, plus once in the middle. Write down these distances.
  6. Average the three distances. Write down this average for the X-axis. Mine was 99.79.
  7. Using calipers, measure the distance across the Y-axis in at least three places. I suggest measuring 10mm from each end, plus once in the middle. Write down these distances.
  8. Average the three distances. Write down this average for the Y-axis. Mine was 99.63.
  9. Next, use this formula to determine new M92 values:
    New M92 value = Desired movement / Actual movement * Current M92 value
    So for example, New M92 for X (100.21) = 100/99.79*100
    So for example, New M92 for Y (100.37) = 100/99.63*100
  10. Create the new M92 command by replacing the X and Y values above with the new calculated values:
    M92 X100.21 Y100.37 Z400.00 E161.30
  11. Place this line in the Startup GCODE in your slicer. In Simplify3D this is placed in the Scripts --> Starting Scrip area. In Slic3r this is in Printer Settings --> Custom G-code.
  12. Re-slice the Calibration square
  13. Re-print the Calibration square
  14. Mark and measure the new calibration square as in steps 5-8 above
  15. Average the distances for X and Y These should now be closer to 100.0mm
  16. If you are satisfied with the results, you are done! If the distances are not as close to 100mm as you desire, if not happy with results, repeat the calibration process.

Note that this test was done with PLA. When you change material, you should re-test dimensions, and may need to re-calibrate your M92 values.

If you want to adjust your Z or E axis, please refer to the Instructables article.

http://www.instructables.com/id/Calibrating-your-3D-printer-using-minimal-filament/

description.text:
This is a remix of the fantastic interlocking card plate by KU4TP. The original design is great, but the cross pieces were not anchored at both ends. This caused a failed print when one curled up and got caught in machinery on my printer!

This remix is the same as the original, but the cross pieces have been extended so that they are anchored on both sides of the frame. This has eliminated the issue for me, and perhaps others will find it useful as well.

I was running my printer on a piece of carpet to isolate vibration. I've been looking for a more permanent solution and saw that some people have used tennis balls with attachment mounts. I wanted something smaller and found these foam rubber practice golf balls. They are made of medium density foam rubber with a tough exterior. They are only 41 mm in diameter which make them compact and low profile. I designed a mount that accepts a 1/4-20 or 7 mm hex head screw. The screw pushes in from the bottom and rests in a hexagon shaped pocket. The mount screws into the threaded end of my 2020 extrusion on my HyperCube printer. The balls are retained by four small barbs on the inside rim of the mount. They are pressed firmly in place but can be pried out if replacement is needed. The balls are cheap and readily available. Here's what I used:
https://www.amazon.com/PrideSports-Practice-Balls-Count-Yellow/dp/B00466W9X0

Be sure to print with supports.

These mounts quiet vibration transmitted to the table and do not introduce any printing artifacts.

1: Skein the STL file at 0.27 layer height, which will make it exactly 3 layers thick. The Brachistochrone problem is famous in physics. It attempts to find the shape of the ramp that will allow a marble to roll under gravity from point A to point B in the least time. It was solved by Newton and Bernoulli and found to be a cycloid. This shape is a tradeoff between the considerations of minimizing the total path length, while still allowing the marble to be low, where it moves faster. In fact, sometimes the optimal track actually dips below point B, but still ends up being faster because of the increase in speed.

The Latin phrase on the front of the model, tanquam ex ungue leonem "we know the lion by his claw" was said by Johann Bernoulli in 1697 about how he knew Isaac Newton was the author of an anonymously submitted solution to his challenge.

References:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brachistochrone_curve

description.text:
See the newest version of this design here! (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2051675)

This phone case design is nearly identical to the previous iteration of this design found here (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2051071) except for one detail. This design has a small lip on the inner edge near the surface of the phone case. This proved effective at holding the phone into the case. As you can see on the bottom edges, I dropped the phone while it was in the case, and it landed such that the bottom pieces partially chipped off.

This is an iPhone 6 case with 5 hex sockets located at various places. Each side around the perimeter of the phone is 2 mm thick, and the back of the phone case is about 4 mm thick. The two socket holes in the center of the case are 1/4 and 5/16 in. The three at the bottom are 1/4, 5/16, and 3/8 in. I made this in Inventor, which has a unit of mm. Cura, or possibly other slicing softwares, naturally use mm as well. So when you input the STL it will be very small. So scale it to the following dimensions. The max X dimenstion is 70.97 and the max Y dimension is 142.14. There is an indention in the bottom half of the phone, the purpose of which is to allow the case to bend easier when inserting and removing the case.
